  "description": "A combination is an unordered selection of objects from a collection — a choice of which objects to include, without regard to the order in which they are chosen. From the letters A, B, C, D, the 3-letter combinations are {A,B,C}, {A,B,D}, {A,C,D}, and {B,C,D} — four in total. The arrangement ABC and the arrangement CBA are different permutations but the same combination, because they involve the same three letters.\nThe number of ways to choose kk objects from nn is the binomial coefficient (nk)=n!k!(n−k)!\\binom{n}{k} = \\frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}. The formula comes from a simple overcounting argument: the number of kk-permutations of nn objects is n!(n−k)!\\frac{n!}{(n-k)!} (you choose kk objects and arrange them). But each combination corresponds to k!k! permutations (all possible orderings of the same kk objects). Dividing the number of permutations by k!k! eliminates the duplicate orderings and gives the number of combinations.\n",
